;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Stop "Stop playing"

    @{u}Stop@{uu}


	Stop will cause the CD to stop playing. Stop will also cancel the Preview
	mode and Pause if selected.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node play "Play track"

    @{u}Play@{uu}


	When pressed, Interplay will start playing the actual track. If no
	track is specified, it will start playing the first audio-track on the CD.
	If the CD-door is open when play is pressed, it will close automatically
	and start playing track 1 after initializing.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node pause "Pauses the current track"

    @{u}Pause@{uu}


	Just like a normal CD-player, this pauses the CD. By pressing the button
	again, the CD will continue where it was paused.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Prev "Preview 10 seconds of each track"

    @{u}Preview@{uu}


	The preview-function is quite handy when you shall browse thru all
	the tracks on the CD. When pressing the Preview button, the player
	will start from the beginning and play 10 seconds of each track
	until it reaches the last track. To disable this function, just press
	Stop.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node counter "Time Counter"

    @{u}Counter@{uu}


	The counter displays the elapsed time of the track/CD.

		00:00:00
		|  |  |___: Seconds 0-59
		|  |______: Minutes 1-59
		|_________: Hours   0-99


	Sometimes when you bump the CD-Rom a bit, it will skip back or forth a bit.
	This will make the timer go wrong. Rememer that this is a problem which
	is caused by the cd-rom player, and not our program. We have no way of 
	correcting this problem because it's a hardware problem. However, this
	seldomly happen on newer CD-Rom drives anyway. So, if this happens, and 
	the timer reaches 00:00:00 before the song is ended, it will come up with
	a funny message in the counter-window :-)

	(However, we do not encourage you to kick your player to see this)
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Skip "Skip tracks"

    @{u}< Skip, Skip >@{uu}


	Skip let's you skip back and forth to choose one special track to play.
	If the player is in 'stop' mode and you press skip in either directions,
	the player won't start playing before you press play. This gives you the
	possibility to skip to a special track and start playing it whenever
	you want. Name of the tracks will of course be displayed too.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Search "Search back and forth"

    @{u}ę Back, Forth Ľ@{uu}


	This function is used to fastforward the CD. Search is used when you
	want to skip to one part of a track. If you don't like the beginning
	of  a track, you simply search thru the track using Back or Forth until
        you reach the part you like. Search-speed is about 8 times faster than
	normal playing-time. Search functions works both forward and backward.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node TrackSlider "Use the track slider to choose a track"

    @{u}Track Slider@{uu}


	One can very fast select a track by moving the slider to the desired track.
	For instance, if you want to skip from track 1 to track 56, it would require
	you to press Skip 56 times, but by using the slider, this is easily done by
	just moving it to the position. The track-number is also shown to the right,
	of the slider, so it's easy to keep control of which track you're on.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Eject "Open the CD tray"

    @{u}Eject@{uu}


	This button will open the CD-door, or close it if the door is open.
	The door is toggled when Eject-button is pressed. PLAY and PREV buttons
	can also be pressed to close the CD-door, and if you press PLAY or PREV
	when the door is open, Interplay will start playing after the door has
	closed. If you activate "Autoplay CD after insert" in the  prefs menu, the
	Interplay will automatically start playing track nr. 1 of the CD as
	soon as it has been inserted. Also, if the tray is open when you start
	Interplay, it will automatically close.

	(Not available on CD32)
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node SpeedSearch "Let's you select where in the track to start, and shows percentage"

    @{u}Speed-search@{uu}


	This is one of the best routines in this new version, and it did
	require quite some planning and programming before it worked 100%
	correct. How you use it is that you use the mouse to control the
	slider to the left of the search buttong (Back/Forth) to decide
	where in the track it shall start playing. The digits on the right
	most side of the slider tells you the percentage of the track that
	has been played. This slider will be updated realtime while you are
	playing a track, and also will the digits. You can move the slider
	while playing also, and it saves you quite some time if you want to
	hear the last part of the song if you don't wanna spend minutes of
	searching forward. Also notice that the timer is following the sliders
	action so the time adn the slider-position is always correct.
	However, it has been known to differ Ī1-2 seconds some times,
	but it's nothing serious. This function also works in all the 4
	time-toggle modes.

	E.g, if you move it to 50, it will start playing in the middle of the track.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Minimize "Minimizes the playerwindow a little"

    @{u}Minimize@{uu}


	This is a handy function for those who don't want Interplay to take up
	so much space on the screen. Even though you might have removed the
	List-view, the player can sometimes look to big. So, we included this
	function, on request of a user, which minimizes the window even more and
	leaves only the most important buttons available. Remember that you can
	press the same button once more to maximize the player window. 
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Timetoggler "Toggles how to show time on the counter"

    @{u}Time-toggler@{uu}


	We added the ability to show the elapsed time of a track, of the whole
	CD and time left of the track and the CD. By toggling the button, the
	counter will change according to the mode selected. These modes are:


		* Show Elapsed track-time
	
		* Show Time left of track
	
		* Show Elapsed CD time
	
		* Show Time left on CD
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Program "Opens the program window"

    @{u}Program@{uu}


	Let's the user make his/her own programs for specific CD's. This means
	that each time you insert a CD, Interplay will load the specific program
	made for this CD. If you make a program for a CD, and press SAVE, then
	this will be the program to be loaded next time the CD is inserted.
	Remember also that you can choose whether the program for a CD shall be
        auto-loaded each time you insert the CD or whether you have to load it
	manually using the Program-Editor.

        This is a list of the buttons/funtions in the Program-Editor:


    @{u}The Panel:@{uu}             Here you have buttons from 0-9 including + and -.
                           Using the buttons from 0-9 you choose a track from 0-99
	  @{"1" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"2" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"3" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"+" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!}     and by pressing the button "Add to program", this track
	  @{"4" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"5" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"6" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"-" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!}     will be added to the current program. You can also see
	  @{"7" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"8" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"9" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} @{"0" link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!}     that the number you chosed is displayed in the "Actual
			   track to add"-stringbox to the right. By pressing + or -
			   you can increase/decrease this number by one each time
			   you press + or -.

    @{u}Programmed Tracks:@{uu}     This is the list that contains the tracks you have
			   programmed. First track starts from upper-left corner,
                           and last track at lower-right corner. This list contains
                           only the number of th tracks. To view the name of the
			   tracks you have programmed, look at the window below. 
			   Here you have a list of all the track-names programmed.

    @{u}Buttons:@{uu}    @{"Click here for a description of the buttons" link ProgramEditorButtons}

@endnode
@node ProgramEditorButtons "Buttons in the Program-Editor..."

    @{u}Buttons in the Program-Editor@{uu}


	@{"   Rotate left      " link Rotate}

        @{"   Rotate right     " link Rotate} 

	@{"   Reverse order    " link Reverse} 

        @{"   Shuffle          " link Shuffle} 

        @{"   Delete last      " link DeleteLast} 

	@{"   Load program     " link LoadProgram}

	@{"   Save program     " link SaveProgram}

	@{"   Clear Program    " link ResetProgram} 

	@{"   Ok               " link Ok}

@endnode
@node Rotate "Rotate the data..."

    @{u}Rotate Left/Right@{uu}


	These two buttons will let you rotate the data either left or right in
	the actual script.
@endnode
@node Reverse "Reverse order of the tracks..."

    @{u}Reverse@{uu}


	Reverse order of all the programmed tracks. I.e. if you have programmed the 
	tracks "01 02 03 04" and press Reverse, the result will be "04 03 02 01".
@endnode
@node Shuffle "Shuffle the order of the tracks randomly..."

    @{u}Shuffle@{uu}


	If you want Interplay to shuffle the order of the tracks you have programmed,
	simply press Shuffle, and the order will become randomly.
@endnode

@node DeleteLast "Delete last programmed track..."

    @{u}Delete last@{uu}


	If you regret a programmed track, just press this button to delete the
	track. Also, if you wan tot delete the second-last programmed track, you
	can simply press rotate-right then delete-last, and rotate-left again.
	This lets you delete any programmed track you want without having to
	undo all levels back to the one you want to delete.
@endnode
@node LoadProgram "Load an already existing program from disk..."

    @{u}Load Program@{uu}


        By pressing this button, the program (if one) for this specific CD will
	be loaded. If there are no existing program for this CD already, you
        can make one and press @{"Save Program" link SaveProgram} or if not,
	Interplay will use the "1..2..3..4..5..6..7..etc" combination.

	To prevent Interplay by auto-loading the program for a specific CD
	when inserted, just disable "auto-load program" in the @{"prefs-window" link preferences}.
@endnode
@node SaveProgram "Save the current program to disk..."

    @{u}Save program@{uu}


	When you have made a program for a CD, pressing Save will save that
	specific program for that specific CD. This means that the next time
	you insert that CD, that specific program belongs to that CD. As you
        may have already understood, each CD gets its own unique program so
	that you can have a program with your favourite songs for each CD you
	have.
@endnode
@node ResetProgram "Clears the current program..."

    @{u}Clear program@{uu}


	If you want to cancel a program, press Clear. This will clear the program
	and let you play all tracks independantly of the program previously 
	loaded/programmed.
@endnode
@node Ok "Accept a program and return to Interplay..."

    @{u}Ok@{uu}


	Pressing Ok will return to Interplay and use the actual program.
	To disable a program, open the program editor and press @{"Clear-Program" link ResetProgram}
	
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node StatusWindow "Status window"

    @{u}Status window@{uu}


	This window shows the status of the player. It will echo
	the different states you set the player to, and you can then
	see what the player is doing even when the volume is turned off.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@Node Preferences "Using the preference-window"

    @{u}Preferences@{uu}


	This window lets the user to configure Interplay to forfill his needs
	at startup and during use. We've included quite some features here
	this time. These are as follows...



	@{u}Checkbox-Features:@{uu}

  
        @{"./" link CFG_bv1} Open Listview on startup    @{"./" link CFG_bv6} Iconify on startup          
        @{"./" link CFG_bv2} Halt CD-Motor on stop       @{"./" link CFG_bv7} Joystick/Joypad support     
        @{"./" link CFG_bv3} Autoplay CD after insert    @{"./" link CFG_bv8} Minimize on startup         
        @{"./" link CFG_bv4} Update/Use Interplay.list   @{"./" link CFG_bv9} Autoload specific CD-Program
        @{"./" link CFG_bv5} Number tracks in listview





@{" Requesters " link Requesters} @{" Directories " link directories} @{" Public Screens " link PubScreen} @{" Coordinates " link Coordinates} @{" Lines in listwindow " link LW-Lines}

@endnode


@node CFG_bv1 "Open listview on startup"

    @{u}Open listview on startup@{uu}


	If ON, the listview window will pop up every time Interplay is started.                            
@endnode

@node CFG_bv2 "Halt CD_Motor on stop"

    @{u}Halt the motor@{uu}


	Stops the motor when the user press Stop or when you exit/quit Interplay.
@endnode

@node CFG_bv3 "Autoplay the CD when inserted"

    @{u}Autoplay@{uu}


	When a CD is inserted and the tray is closed, Interplay will start 
	playing track 1 when this mode is activated. Or if a program is 
	defined for this CD, it will load this if it is specified that 
	programs should be autoloaded when CD inserted.
@endnode

@node CFG_bv4 "Update/Use interplay.list"

    @{u}Update/Use Interplay.list@{uu}


	If this switch if OFF, Interplay will ignore the information found in
	the @{i}Interplay.list.@{ui} Also, the list won't be updated nor used in
        any way if this mode if OFF. If it's ON, then all actions will be stored
	in the Interplay.list.
@endnode

@node CFG_bv5 "Number tracks in listeview"

    @{u}Number tracks@{uu}


	If ON, Interplay will insert tracknumbers in front of the trackname in
	the listwindow. Very handy if you want to know which trackunmber a 
	desired track in the list has. Remember that if this switch also works
	with the list-view in the Program-Editor.
@endnode

@node CFG_bv6 "Iconify on startup"

    @{u}Iconify@{uu}


	When selected (ON) Interplay will start as iconified, and you can open
	the player again by choosing it from the Tools-Menu in the workbench.
@endnode

@node CFG_bv7 "Use Joystick/Joypad"

    @{u}Joystick/Joypad@{uu}


	Lets you use Interplay with the Joypad/Joystick.
                             
	  Up  : Start	Down : Stop
	  Left: <Skip	Right: Skip>
@endnode
@node CFG_bv8 "Minimize Interplay on startup"

    @{u}Minimize@{uu}


	Is this feature is @{b}on@{ub}, you are able to tell Interplay to shrink
	the window even more a the time it's started. This can be handy if you
	think the player-window already is too large.

	Read more about @{"Minimize" link minimize}here.
@endnode

@node CFG_bv9 "Autoload specific CD-Program"

    @{u}Autoloading@{uu}


	Loads a CD's specific program when the CD is inserted. (If it doesn't find
	a program, an error message will appear in the status window)	
@endnode
@endnode

@node Requesters "Requesters in the Config-Window..."

    @{u}Font Requester@{uu} (@{b}Not implemented yet due to some slight bugs@{ub})


	The font-requester enables the user to chose the font he/she likes best.
	The GUI is font-adaptive, and all the graphics will follow the font-size
	the actual font has.

	Use the file-requester to choose your favourite font, or simply enter the
	font name in the string-box to the right of the file-requester button.
        You can also enter the font-size directly by entering a number directly
	in the smaller stringbox to the right of the file-stringbox.
@endnode

@node Directories "Directory-spsifications in the config-window..."

    @{u}Directory of Interplay.list@{uu}


	If you are not happy with where the Interplay.list is saved, you can
	here enter your favourite directory where you want it to be saved.
	You can only specify the name of the directory, _not_ the filename.
	The datafile will alwys be called Interplay.list no matter what.

	@{b}Interplay.prog will be saved at the same location as the Interplay.list@{ub}
@endnode
@node PubScreen "Public screen selection..."

    @{u}Choose public-screen@{uu}


	If you want the Interplay to pop up on another screen than the workbench-
	screen, you enter the name of the public-screen here, or you chose the name
	from the available pub-screens from the list by pressing the file-requester.
	(Recommended to press this, because you cannot Install the player on all
	windows since not all support it. This list will tell you the ones available).

	Very handy if you don't remember, or know, the name of the screen you want
	Interplay to appear on.
@endnode
@node coordinates "Window coordinates..."

    @{u}Coordinates@{uu}


	Enter the coordinates (X and Y are upper left corner of the window) to
	specify where you want the Interplay-window to be. Also, if you place
	the Interplay window on the place of the screen where you want it to
	appear, you just open the prefs and you will find the coordinates from
	where you put the window in the X and Y coordinate stringboxes. This
	means that you don't have to KNOW the coordinates, instead you just
	press SAVE CONFIG and the next time you start Interplay, the window will
	pop up the place it was before you saved the config.
@endnode
@node LW-Lines "Lines in listview window..."

    @{u}Lines in listwindow@{uu} (@{b}Not implemented yet@{ub})


	Enter the number of lines you want the listwindow to be. You
	may enter numbers from 1 up to the length you want depending
        on your vertical screensize.
@endnode
@endnode

;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Trackname "Displays the name of the track"

    @{u}Trackname@{uu}


	Read more about it in the @{"list-view" link List} section where it is also
	explained how the Artist-list functions work.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node loop "Loop functions"

    @{u}Loop functions@{uu}


	There are three different loop-modes. These are as follows:


	No Loop : will inactivate all kinds of looping of track/CD.

	Loop    : will loop the actual track. When the end of the track has
		  been reached, it will skip back to the beginning of the track
		  and play it over again.

	Loop CD : starts playing the CD all over again when the last track has
		  finished.


	* Loop is not available in Preview mode.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node GAname "Group/Artist -name"

    @{u}Group/Artist -name@{uu}


	Read more about in the @{"list-view" link List}section where it is also
	explained how the Artist-list functions work.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node random "Randomly play tracks"

    @{u}Random@{uu}


	By switching on the Random-checkbox the player will choose tracks randomly
	when in Play-mode. Press the checkbox again to turn off random-mode.

	The random functions will of course also work on user-defined programs
	made with the program-editor.
@endnode
;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node list "Show the Artist-List editor"

    @{u}Artist list@{uu}


	A very good feature which enables the user to write the names
	for the specific track so that Interplay shows the real trackname
	instead of just its tracknumber. To do this, simply enter, in the upper
	string-box, the name of the track. Press tab or use the mouse to move
	the cursor to the other string-box below. Now enter the name of the
	Group/artist or the name of the CD (You choose). This information is
	saved in an info file ("Interplay.list", user-defined placement) which
	hold information on how many tracks are on the CD, name of tracks, and
	that CD's unique index-code. This index code is just a number generated
	based on CD time and number of tracks. By using this code, Interplay
	will know which CD you insert, and then display its proper infomation.

	If you press the "Open Listview" checkbox below the status-window, the
	player-window will expand, and a list of all the tracknames will come up.
	Also, if you press the "Open Listview" again, it will close.
	Now you can even press the name of the track you want to listen to. This
	feature is good to have if you want to listen to a track and you only remember
	its name. You can then check the list instead of having to read on the cover
	of the CD to find out which track the song is on. The actual track
	is high-lighted with a blue bar.

	This is how the system works. Fill in the proper information in the boxes.
	The upper box is used for the name of the track, and the box below is used
	for the name of the group. Here is an example of how it is done:

	@{"        Marooned         " link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} <name of track>

	@{"       Pink Floyd        " link ...cos_this_is_a_dummy-link_Actually!!} <name of group/artist>

	Interplay will make a datafile which carries the name of the tracks.
	All versions of Interplay come with a datafile.
@endnode
@node listview "Listview..."
 
    @{u}Listview@{uu}


	When opened (by pressing @{"Open listview" link Listview}) you can look at all the names
	the the tracks on the CD (if they have been @{"registered" link list} in the list).

	Otherwise, Interplay will call the tracks by their tracknumbers (1,2..n)
@endnode
;******************************************************************************
@node ARexx "Using the ARexx Interface"

    @{u}ARexx in Interplay@{uu}

    
        Interplay's internal ARexx interface offers the ability to control
        its functions via a script. See the @{"ARexx Document" link "ARexx.guide/Main"} for more information.
@endnode
;******************************************************************************
@node Menues "Using the menues in Interplay"

    @{u}Using the menues@{uu}


	Interplay has also got some menu-functions.

	@{"Menues in the Main window          " link MENU_Main}
	@{"Menues in the Prefs window         " link MENU_Prefs}
	@{"Menues in the Program-Editor window" link MENU_Prog}
@endnode

@node MENU_Main "Menues in the main window"

    @{u}Here are the menu-options in the main window:@{uu}


	Project:
		About.......................The usual @{"About-requester" link About}
		Iconify.....................@{"Iconifies" link Iconify} the window.
		Quit........................Quits Interplay

	Window:
		Preferences.................Opens the @{"prefs-window  " link preference}
		Program editor..............Opens the @{"program-editor" link Program} window
@endnode
@node Iconify "Iconify Interplay..."

    @{u}Iconify@{uu}


	Interplay can also be iconified. This means that you doesn't have to have
	the player on the Wb screen all the time, it can still function while being
	iconified. To Iconify, you just choose ICONIFY from the main-menu. What 
        happens	next is that the window disappears, but the music still plays. To
        'get it back' from its Zombi-sleep, you can choose "Interplay" from the 
        "Tools" menu in the workbench. When selecting this, Interplay will pop up
        again exactly where it was left and how it was left as if nothing had
        happened.
@endnode

@node MENU_Prefs

    @{u}Here are the menu-otions in the preference window@{uu}


	Project:
		About prefs.................Information about the prefs-window
		Quit prefs..................Quits prefs, and returns to the main
                                            window

	Window:
		Use config..................Uses the actual config without saving
		Save config.................Save the actual config for future use
@endnode

@node MENU_Prog

    @{u}Here are the menu-options in the Program-Editor window@{uu}


	Project:
		Load program................Loads an already saved program from disk
		Save program................Save actual program to the disk
		About Program-editor........About this program-editor
		Quit Program-editor.........Quits and returns to the main window

	Effects:
		@{"Rotate left " link rotate}...............Rotates the tracks one step to the left
		@{"Rotate right" link rotate}...............Rotates the tracks one step to the right
		@{"Shuffle     " link shuffle}...............Shuffles the currently programmed tracks 
                                            randomly
		@{"Reverse     " link reverse}...............Reverses the current program
@endnode
@node Rotate "Rotate the data in the program left/right"

    @{u}Reverse@{uu}


	The rotate buttons will roll the data in the program you've made either
	to the left, or to the right depending on which button you press.
@endnode

@node Shuffle "Shuffles the data in the program randomly"

    @{u}Shuffle@{uu}


	This is will shuffle all the tracks you've programmed into a random
	order.
@endnode
@node Reverse "Reverses the data in the program"

    @{u}Reverse@{uu}


 	Press this, and the last track will become the first track, and the
	first track will become the last track. In short, the whole program
	will be inverted into a "what's last, will become first"-mode.

	To undo your reverse, simply press reverse once more
@endnode
;******************************************************************************
